City of Charlotte Safe Streets for All

After successfully securing $4.47 million to prevent pedestrian deaths and injuries The City of Charlotte is evaluating their proposed intersection upgrade locations. You have been enlisted as a consultant and tasked to conduct an analysis of their data and proposal. You should use appropriate data processing and analysis methods to produce an overview report which summarises the patterns revealed in the data. It is expected that at least some of the methods you use will relate to the spatial dimensions of the data. Your report should include a brief introduction including relevant contextual information at the beginning and a critical review of your findings at the end. You must include at least one map.

Initial project scope

In this project, the City of Charlotte received funding to install equipment aimed at eliminating pedestrian-related crashes. Due to limited resources, we must prioritize intersections with the highest potential for reducing such incidents. We can calculate crash density for each area, such as crashes per square kilometer or per capita, and analyze the temporal trends. Finally, we will use the K-means algorithm to identify the most critical intersections within the community scale and uncover any hidden risk points beyond these locations.

Research question and aim

  • Research question: Are areas with high population density more likely to experience pedestrian crashes, or are crash occurrences independent of population density patterns?
  • Primary aim: To investigate the relationship between population density and pedestrian crash rates and analyze the spatial patterns of pedestrian crashes in Charlotte to identify areas with high potential for reducing such incidents.
  • Specific objectives:
    1. Examine temporal trends from 2019-2023 to know the pattern of pedestrian crashes (line chart)
    2. Analyze spatial distribution of pedestrian crashes across Charlotte community districts (kernel density map )
    3. calculate crash density for each area, such as crashes per square kilometer or per capita to characterize each area (K-means clustering)

Limitations and Constraints

  • We don’t know how the government initially evaluated their proposed intersections. Local residents might have a better understanding of the actual situation.
  • More accidents tend to occur in city centers, but this doesn’t necessarily mean they are caused by road design or signage. Therefore, it may be important to focus on suburban areas with less data.

Data Sources

  • City of Charlotte Fatal or Serious Injury Crashes (2019 -2023) https://data.charlottenc.gov/datasets/charlotte::fatal-or-serious-injury-crashes/about
    • This datasets Shows the location of fatal and serious injury crashes in Charlotte from 2019 to 2023
    • key columns: CRSH_ID, DATE_VAL_Y, CRSH_TYPE(eg:Pedestrian, Left turn, same roadway), geometry(point)
  • Safe Streets and Roads for All proposed intersection(2024) https://data.charlottenc.gov/datasets/charlotte::safe-streets-for-all-grant-projects-1/explore?location=35.202947%2C-80.818650%2C10.55
    • This dataset contains the proposed intersection locations and their project types(eg:Pedestrian Hybrid Beacons (PHB), Rectangular Rapid Flashing Beacon (RRFB)).
    • key columns: GISID, ProjectType (eg:Pedestrian Hybrid Beacons (PHB), Rectangular Rapid Flashing Beacon (RRFB)), geometry(point)
  • Commuting block groups(2019) https://data.charlottenc.gov/datasets/charlotte::census-commuting-block-groups-1/explore?location=35.217378%2C-80.888231%2C11.83
    • This dataset shows the commuting status in different ways of each area in Charlotte.
    • key columns: GEOID10, Workers_16_and_older, Drove_alone, Carpool, Public_Transportation, Walked
  • Census Population Block Groups(2019) https://data.charlottenc.gov/datasets/charlotte::census-population-block-groups-2/explore?location=35.258898%2C-80.807850%2C9.97
    • This dataset shows the demographic information of each area in Charlotte.
    • Key columns: GEOID10, Population, Shape__Area

Calcualte the index for clustering

#step 1: calculate the index for clustering
#cloume crash density = crash_count/(Population/ Shape__Area
#walk_public_ratio = (Walked + Public_Transportation)/ Workers_16_and_older 

cluster_df <- final_df %>%
  mutate(
    crash_density = ifelse(Population > 0 & Shape__Area > 0, 
                           crash_count / (Population / Shape__Area), 
                           NA),
    walk_public_ratio = ifelse(Workers_16_and_older > 0, 
                               (Walked + Public_Transportation) / Workers_16_and_older, 
                               NA)
  )

# standardize the index for clustering
cluster_df <- cluster_df %>%
  mutate(
    crash_density_norm = (crash_density - min(crash_density, na.rm = TRUE)) / 
                         (max(crash_density, na.rm = TRUE) - min(crash_density, na.rm = TRUE)),
    walk_public_ratio_norm = (walk_public_ratio - min(walk_public_ratio, na.rm = TRUE)) / 
                             (max(walk_public_ratio, na.rm = TRUE) - min(walk_public_ratio, na.rm = TRUE))
  )

# check NA values
sapply(cluster_df, function(x) sum(is.na(x)))
##                GEOID10   Workers_16_and_older            Drove_alone 
##                      0                      0                      0 
##                Carpool  Public_Transportation                 Walked 
##                      0                      0                      0 
##             Population            Shape__Area            crash_count 
##                      0                      0                      0 
##               geometry          crash_density      walk_public_ratio 
##                      0                      2                      2 
##     crash_density_norm walk_public_ratio_norm 
##                      2                      2
clustering_data <- cluster_df %>%
  filter(!is.na(crash_density_norm) & !is.na(walk_public_ratio_norm)) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  select(crash_density_norm, walk_public_ratio_norm)


set.seed(50) 
kmeans_result <- kmeans(clustering_data, centers = 4) 

cluster_df$cluster <- NA
non_na_indices <- which(!is.na(cluster_df$crash_density_norm) & !is.na(cluster_df$walk_public_ratio_norm))
cluster_df$cluster[non_na_indices] <- kmeans_result$cluster

# check cluster_df$cluster
table(cluster_df$cluster, useNA = "ifany")

       x = "Crash Density",

  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 12),
    legend.text = element_text(size = 10)
  ) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#ff9320", "#69fda9", "#ff5a5a", "#a2ff8b"))

- The current clustering results are not very good due to a lack of time to process outlier data. However, it can be observed that most areas are concentrated in scenarios with low public transportation and walked rate and there tend to have higher crash density.

custom_colors <- c("#ff9320", "#69fda9", "#ff5a5a", "#a2ff8b") 

ggplot(data = cluster_df) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = as.factor(cluster)), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = custom_colors, name = "Cluster") +
  labs(title = "Spatial Distribution of Clusters",
       subtitle = "K-means Clustering of Crash Density and Walk/Public Ratio") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14),

  )

This map shows the spatial distribution of k-means clusters based on Crash Density and Walk/Public Transportation Ratio. Eventhough the clustering results are not very good, It could say that the city center might safer than other areas.

Conclusion

  • Although the frequency of accidents is higher in the city center, certain suburban or less populated areas still pose safety risks. The clustering results indicate that areas with low public transportation and walking rates tend to have higher accident densities, which may require further research and policy intervention. Due to time constraints, the clustering results may not be ideal, and future efforts could focus on handling outlier data to improve the accuracy of the analysis.
